Sorry for the delayed response...
You'll need to build libMesh statically as a prerequisite. MOOSE only understands how it needs to be built, based on how libMesh is built. In order to do this via our Conda packages, it will be necessary to create a new environment, which only contains what libMesh needs (moose-petsc). We also need Python. I will install moose-tools in order to obtain a version we support (3.7 -3.10):
mamba activate base    # get back to the original environment
mamba create -n petsc moose-petsc moose-tools
mamba activate petsc
From within this environment we can now build libMesh with static options. I am going to include some cleaning commands to clean up any previous build attempts. Keep in mind these git commands will delete any uncommitted work (so be sure to save your work if you have changes)!
cd ~/projects/moose
git clean -xfd
git submodule foreach --recursive git clean -xfd
Now I am going to set some environment variables to speed up my libMesh build:
export MOOSE_JOBS=28   # replace this number with how many cores your machine has
export METHODS=opt
We are ready to build libMesh statically:
scripts/update_and_rebuild_libmesh.sh --enable-all-static --enable-static
Once finished, we can now instruct MOOSE to build, and it will automatically be built statically:
cd test
make -j $MOOSE_JOBS
Everything we just built manually was statically included.
